k blends theoretical inquiry and real-world case study, making Callaghan’s study a unique insight into religiously-inspired heterosexism and genderism. She uncovers the causes and effects of the long-standing disconnect between Canadian Catholic schools and the Charter by comparing the treatment of and attitudes towards lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, and queer teachers and students in these publicly-funded systems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aDiscrimination in educationzCanadavCase studies. 0aHeterosexism in schoolszCanadavCase studies. 0aHomophobia in schoolszCanadavCase studies. 0aSchool environmentzCanadavCase studies. 7aEDUCATION / Educational Policy & Reform / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2018z978311060679940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751796040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487517960423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487517960.jpg  a978-3-11-060679-9  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK